{
  "texts": [
    "2):It presents a measure of the amount of information contained within a certain amount of data (eg: a file).",
    "For example, if we have two files, one containing the words ''today it is raining'' and the second ''today it is raining today it is raining today it is raining'', the amount of information entropy of the two files is (approximately) the same, even though the size of the two files is different.The term ''approximately'' is used since it is not possible to calculate the amount of information entropy precisely because it is related to the Kolmogorov complexity which practically seeks for the size of the smallest program that can create a data file.",
    "This size, unfortunately, is a number that cannot be calculated, due to three main reasons: The programming language, the halting problem, and the infinite number of possible programs one must seek to find the shortest (1)h a i = log 2 1 w i (2) H(A) = ∑ w i >0 w i h a i = ∑ w i >0 w i log 2 1 w i = - ∑ w i >0 w i log 2 w ione.",
    "There can, however, be a very good approximation of an upper bound on the information entropy by making a histogram of how often each symbol appears, treating that histogram such as a weighted N-sided die (a Probability Mass Function or PMF), and calculating the entropy of this die.",
    "This size is related to Huffman compression [43], which uses a histogram of the data and gives shorter bit patterns to the symbols that appear the most."
  ]
}